        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real native advertising examples</h2>
        <p>Three examples of native advertising producing better results than equivalent display spend.</p>

        <h3>Example 1: Law firm advertorial at $47 cost per lead</h3>
        <p>A regional personal injury firm in Dallas paid $2,500 for a sponsored article titled "5 Things to Do Immediately After a Car Accident" on the city's largest news website. The placement generated 340 visits in its first month at a $47 cost per lead, compared to $185 per lead for Google Ads targeting identical keywords. The article remained indexed and continued driving organic traffic for 14 months after the paid campaign ended.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: CRM startup LinkedIn native vs banners</h3>
        <p>A CRM startup ran LinkedIn Sponsored Content styled as a founder's organic post, sharing proprietary data about sales follow-up timing. The campaign achieved 3x engagement versus their banner campaigns and 40% lower cost per click. The key difference: the post opened with a genuinely useful data point rather than a product pitch.</p>

        <h3>Example 3: HVAC company content recommendation</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company ran Outbrain campaigns linking to their blog post "8 Signs Your AC Is About to Die." Articles appeared as recommended reading on weather and home improvement sites at $0.35 cost per click. The page ranked organically within three months for "signs AC is failing" — the paid native campaign seeded enough engagement signals to accelerate organic ranking.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Native advertising vs content marketing — which to use</h2>
        <p>The two are complementary, not competing. Native advertising is the amplification mechanism; content marketing is the asset being amplified. Using one without the other wastes the opportunity each creates.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Choose native advertising when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need traffic now, not in 6 months</li>
              <li>You want to test content resonance before investing in organic</li>
              <li>You're entering a new market or audience segment</li>
              <li>Organic reach is declining on your key social platforms</li>
              <li>You have a proven content asset worth amplifying</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Choose content marketing when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You're building long-term organic search rankings</li>
              <li>Budget requires durable, compounding returns</li>
              <li>Your audience distrusts paid promotion</li>
              <li>You're building thought leadership over time</li>
              <li>Campaign-limited traffic doesn't serve your model</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for native advertising</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with value, not product.</strong> The best-performing native ads open with a useful data point, counterintuitive insight, or practical tip — not "Buy our product." Readers engage with the content first; conversion happens through the content experience.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the platform's voice exactly.</strong> Study 20 organic posts on your target platform before writing one native ad. Copy the headline length, image style, opening hook format, and tone. Anything that feels "ad-like" triggers the scroll reflex you're trying to avoid.</li>
          <li><strong>Disclose clearly but design carefully.</strong> The FTC requires visible disclosure. Put "Sponsored" or "Paid Post" where readers expect to see a byline or tag — not in 8pt grey text at the bottom. Clear disclosure builds trust; hidden disclosure destroys it when discovered.</li>
          <li><strong>Test 5-10 headline variants per campaign.</strong> Native ad CTR is almost entirely headline-driven. A/B test aggressively before scaling spend. The difference between a 0.3% and 0.9% CTR on the same content is usually just the headline.</li>
          <li><strong>Pair native spend with organic content that can rank.</strong> If your native content is published on your own domain, optimize it for organic search simultaneously. Native ads seed engagement signals; SEO captures the long-term value.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — publishing without FTC disclosure</div>
          <p>The FTC has issued enforcement actions against brands and publishers for inadequate native ad disclosure. "Disclosure" buried at the bottom of the page or in a colour that blends with the background does not meet the standard. The label must be clearly visible before the reader engages with the content — not after. Violations carry fines up to $50,120 per incident.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common native advertising mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Making it too promotional</strong> — opening with product features kills engagement. Readers came for content, not a pitch deck.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile formatting</strong> — over 60% of native ad clicks happen on mobile. Headlines and images that work on desktop often fail on a 375px screen.</li>
          <li><strong>Running the same creative for 90 days</strong> — native audiences experience creative fatigue faster than search audiences. Refresh creative every 3-4 weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Sending traffic to product pages</strong> — native-driven traffic is early-funnel. Send them to an educational article or landing page, not a checkout page.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping disclosure on UGC-style ads</strong> — influencer posts and user-generated style ads require the same FTC disclosure as traditional sponsored content.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
