            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Native ads consistently outperform traditional display, with click-through rates running 5-10x higher than banner ads. Research from Sharethrough and IPG Media Lab found native ads receive 53% more visual attention than standard display. Effectiveness depends heavily on content quality and platform fit.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How much do native ads cost?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Cost-per-click typically ranges from $0.20 to $5.00 depending on platform and targeting. Sponsored articles on major publications cost $1,000-$50,000 per placement. Content recommendation networks like Outbrain and Taboola offer the most affordable entry points, often under $0.50 CPC.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is native advertising ethical?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, when properly disclosed. The FTC requires clear labeling using terms like "Sponsored," "Paid Post," or "Advertisement." Most major platforms enforce labeling standards. Problems arise when disclosure is hidden or visually suppressed — that crosses into deceptive advertising.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
